<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-12-26T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-12-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="150" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d150">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">Hopkins Papers</note>
                                <head>
                                    <hi rend="italic">The British Minister of Supply</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Beaverbrook</hi></persName>)
                                        <hi rend="italic">to the President’s Special Assistant</hi>
                                        (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Hopkins</hi></persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d150fn1">
                                        <p>A memorandum by Hopkins, dated January 3, 1942, attached
                                            to this file, reads as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                                <p>“This is a note that Lord Beaverbrook handed me
                                                  when the Unity of Command was being discussed and
                                                  Churchill seemed to be a stumbling block.</p>
                                                <p>“It was as a result of getting this message that
                                                  I arranged that Marshall see Churchill.”</p>
                                            </quote>
                                        </p>
                                        <p>For the discussion of December 26 to which this note
                                            pertains, see <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_103">p. 103</ref>. For the meeting of
                                            Marshall and Churchill on the morning of December 27,
                                            see <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_108">p. 108</ref>.</p>
                                        <p>A facsimile reproduction of the Beaverbrook note appears
                                            in Sherwood, p. 456.</p>
                                    </note>
                                </head>
                                <opener>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                                        <placeName>
                                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, [<date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-12-26">December 26,
                                            1941</date>.]</dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p>You should work on Churchill. He is being advised. He is open
                                    minded &amp; needs discussion.</p>
                            </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>